fw-work-reason-other-why: The better I got a MVC w/PHP the more I wanted less "do it for me" features like scaffolding and PDO and authentication. I've become more granular in my approach to structuring apps being that I prefer to "craft" application components rather than "generate" them. In layman's terms I prefer to make my own bread rather than buy a loaf from the store. This is ONLY due to my expertise and longevity in PHP, for I have noticed that novice, busy or lazy devs prefer cumbersome frameworks that take the engineering aspect out of development. It's like a restaurant cook who has 24 ingredients to his soup whereas a Michelin starred chef will have 5. Clarity and comprehension are paramount to structuring apps efficiently.
fw-personal-reason-other-why: SlimPHP gives me the freedom to craft apps, especially APIs, efficiently while adhering to conventional standards for application development. There is no CLI, no generators , no behind-the-scenes magic, just raw tools. It's fast and well documented with a very light footprint. I can couple Slim with my own conventions and routing  workflows with ease and clarity.

fw-work-reason-other-why:
Phalcon is simply faster and focused more on whats important as a addition to utilizing PHP than the others many of which are slow, bloated cows.  PHP in itself was never intended for what it is used for today. With Microsofts release of .NET and MONO PHP's days are numbered as is.  I personally know of as of Friday, twenty seven local firms that do development transitioning their code to C# and .NET.  C# & .NET are more robust which is no surprise.  Now the are faster with a lesser resource footprint and Microsoft's unification of technologies is the cherry atop the cake forcing development firms to shift their paradigms.
We recently ported our internal framework from PHP to C#/.NET (mono).  The results are a 172% smaller footprint and nearly 400% faster and we have yet to optimize it.

Simply put, PHP is dead and just does not know it yet.
fw-personal-reason-other-why:
Again,

A framework is to be a tool to help development. Many are way way overkill.  They include functionality that is really more important for enterprise or distributed processing applications on a platform (PHP) that is woefully painful to scale in reasonably managed form.  More is not always better, sometimes its just more.

Whats important in Web Applications is resource usage and processing time per request.  In other words performance.  While there are many piecemeal ways to increase PHP performance they are just that.  The best to increase performance is Phalcon.  They seem to be the only folks that realize the above. Sure, one can throw more hardware at a application to increase its performance and spend more money doing so.  Or one might thing a language/framework meant for web development could handle at least what is considered small level enterprise load.  98% of PHP applications cannot even on decent hardware.  For example, one of our clients has a site that gets 2000-2500 page views a second.  Thats not alot, not at all in fact.  eBay for example will get that in less than a second times 10 easy.

His PHP based site would bog down especially on weekends.  We'd refactored the code many times to pick up more speed.  We even coded a template engine apache extension as well as a database pooling extension and a smart cache (all in assembler).  This improved things by well in excess of 250-300%.  Last November he had us transition his site to DotNetNuke, no more slowdowns, stress testing the install showed he can now not worry about anything for the foreseeable future in as far as traffic load goes.
